AB  - Although there are many conservation and restoration obligations and targets, implementation thereof has so far been insufficient to halt or slow down biodiversity loss. In this context, efforts for ecological restoration must be accelerated. In fulfilling legal obligations and policy targets on restoration, it is important for lawyers and policy makers to understand the underlying ecological concepts. In this article three concepts, that are largely unknown in legal literature, are clarified, namely extinction debt, ecological trap and dark diversity. Their implications for law and policy are analysed and recommendations are made for better integration of these concepts into restoration projects. We recommend more efforts for monitoring beyond the simple presence of certain species, a higher ambition level for restoration measures, a substantial increase in measures for connectivity and restoration measures for 'absent' species.
